We did say that. It's the third item listed in the statement we've published through all our channels.

We are also sharing work others have done relating to AI policing people of color, but would love suggestions for more to share if you have them.

We've also been working on increasing diversity (gender, racial, and location) in our hiring process, and our recent hires reflect this. This is an area where we're still working, of course, and we still need to improve.

We have had an internal diversity and inclusion team for some time, which has given rise to a number of internal initiatives as well as directly led to several of our scholarships â€” a program we've expanded dramatically over the past year.

As the statement says, we're:

1. Donating money
2. Giving the entire team today off to work on a variety of social-justice-related activities

These are the NEW things we're doing, but there are also some ongoing things we've been working on for quite a while:
In case you missed our statement yesterday: https://bit.ly/30dkxrtÂ
https://twitter.com/dataquestio/status/1268591704493391874Â â€¦
Worth listening to if you've got time for podcasts: https://bit.ly/3dywgosÂ

(Here's the full statement as an image) pic.twitter.com/lOObD8WWIT

Looking forward, we have a chance to improve access to education for people around the world. We've started to do this with our work on scholarships. There's much more we can still do. 

I don't know exactly how this will look. But we're going to put in the work to figure it out.
â€¢ We're enabling everyone on our team to take Friday off to focus on social justice initiatives. This can include attending protests, analyzing data, or otherwise supporting others.

â€¢ Dataquest is donating $5,000 to the Equal Justice Initiative (@eji_org).

â€¢ Dataquest will match up to $5,000 in donations that our team members make to organizations fighting systemic inequality in the US or globally.

There isn't a level playing field in America today.

At Dataquest, we have a chance to make a small difference in our communities and in the world. Justice and equality are common values that we share, regardless of where we live.

Here are some of the things we're doing:

Black people are 5 times as likely to be jailed as white people. People of color are 1.5x - 2x as likely to be unemployed as white people.

We owe so much to the generations before us that stood up for their rights. But the fight isn't done.

These protests express our rage at the tragic and senseless killings of George Floyd, Ahmaud Arbery, and Breonna Taylor.

The protests force us to examine stark racial inequality in the US. 235 black people were killed by the police last year.

A note from our CEO @VikParuchuri (THREAD):

It's been a heartbreaking and trying few days for us in the US. We've seen protests in more than 75 cities across the country.

The code exercises on each screen are important for short-term retention. But to cement your new skills into long-term memory and to help you synthesize and think creatively with all the new tools you've learned, each course ends with a guided project.

That's why our lessons are little learning bites followed immediately by exercises that challenge you to write real code to answer real questions about a real dataset.

How do you learn data science? By doing data science. (That's what we think, anyway)

Want to do a marathon ten-hour learning session and earn a new course certificate in a day? You can do that too. 

For us, what's most important is that in EVERY session, you're applying what you've learned by writing REAL code. No fill in the blanks or multiple choice.

Another common question: How do I enroll? When are classes?

Dataquest is self-serve. All you need is a browser. You can sign up for a free account at any time, and you can log in and learn at any time. 

Got 30 minutes free at 3 AM and want to learn about functions? We got you.

One question people often ask us is: where are your videos?

We don't have any. In our experience, it can be tough to learn by watching someone else code. 

Also, reading about programming is a critical skill to develop since virtually all documentation is written.
